node.text:
Today on @thewalkhomepod I share in a way that I haven’t before.
I wanted to start this post by saying something along the lines of “I don’t cry easily,” in reference to today’s episode.
But then I realized that’s not true at all.
I say that in some sort of feigned strength kind of way that clearly still associates crying with weakness.
The truth is that I’m sensitive as hell.
The truth is that I can talk about huge traumas I’ve experienced in such a dissociated state that I go into autopilot & share the story like it’s someone else’s instead of my own.
Today on the pod is different, because I was fully embodied in the retelling of one of the hardest experiences of my life.
I cry as I talk into the mic not because I’m weak, but because I’m finally stepping into the strength of FEELING even the most challenging sensations. 
This is why today’s show is different.
Remembering the best friend I’ve ever known almost on the exact date of her passing is STILL hard- even after 9 years.
Movement is both a way for me to process & for me to avoid. 
Sometimes after a practice of being in total flow, I feel lighter & stuck emotions have worked up & out of me.
And sometimes I open my eyes & realize that I just spent the last hour running away, rather than running into.
Taurus season is always difficult for me.
Sadness lives in bones & grief constricts my throat even when I least expect it.
So I’m making the commitment to myself to use my movement practice for healing, rather than escapism.
And this is real time clip of me moving through grief yesterday 💜 #thewalkhomepod

Favorite music is always @deyadova this is Walking Water live 🙏🏼

node.text:
In fact, the physical practice (asana) is an incredibly small sliver of the whole philosophy pie when we’re talking about yoga.
You can practice in stillness by taking one conscious breath.
You can practice off of your mat by responding rather than reacting.
You can practice in relationships by respecting your edges (boundaries), rather than pushing through them into pain.
You can practice with eyes open or closed.
You can practice on the ground, on a towel, on the sand, on your bed (you don’t NEED a mat, although it’s certainly helpful).
You can practice half (or fully) naked, or covered up from head to toe.
You can practice at home, in a studio (c*vid dependent, obv), in your car, at work, in the shower- ANYWHERE.
Anytime.
With anyone.
Or totally alone.
It’s a practice, like life itself, that has this unique ability to be crafted for each individual person based on their individual needs (which are ever changing, might I add). 
Show up fully for yourself.
Be kind.
Take deep breaths once in a while.
Forgive.
Notice.
That’s it.
The shapes & movement (although quite fun) are secondary.
Just breathe, my friends.
You’ve got this ☀️ #GLOWyogafam

node.text:
I thought it would be nice to share today after an especially emotional private practice yesterday of landing back in my body for the first time all month.
Like life, dedication to this practice ebbs & flows.
I show up to my mat just about daily, but that doesn’t mean I always show up in my body with my breath to the fullest.
Sometimes I’m uninspired to move & create.
Sometimes my mind is running through endless lists of what needs to be done for the five million businesses I’m juggling.
Sometimes I don’t LET myself settle in, because I’m afraid the momentum of my day will die off if I allow myself to relax & unfold. 
But I show up anyways.
Sometimes for five minutes, sometimes for hours on end.
I show up because my body inevitably feels better after (even if it’s just hanging out downdog for a few breaths).
I show up because it helps my patience & grows my love bubble.
I show up because in doing something loving & kind for myself, I’m able to be a better partner, daughter & friend.
Consistency is hard.
Life is noisy.
And it’s easy to get swept up in a culture of productivity.
But I swear the most productive thing of all is the time I spend on this (very dusty) little rectangle that is my mat. 
Getting into that flow state where I’m not guiding the practice, but the practice is coming THROUGH me.
This is where my classes are born.
This is where my teaching is refined.
This is where the magic happens.
Ans I sure can’t wait to share my newest offerings with you!
Filming A LOT of goodness with @alomoves family real soon.
And hosting a MONTH of handstands on Zoom.
All access points to move & groove with me can be found through the link in my bio.
See you on the mat, my friends 🌈 #GLOWyogafam

Today I shared my interview on @thewalkhomepod with @themoon.mother where we talked about Human Design in relation to Mental Health.
In this live, @themoon.mother does a direct reading of my chart, while also sharing overviews of other types, authorities & strategies. 
I’m an Manifestor, 3/5 profile- so we do heavily discuss these two areas.
However, if you’re another type or profile, you can learn more on my episode with her.
Or, contact @themoon.mother directly for sessions & readings.
The biggest takeaway from our chat is that Human Design is really a permission slip.
It’s a tool of empowerment to better understand yourself & those you’re in relationship with, rather than something to condition or limit you.
This system is all about stepping into who you already are & doing so with self-assurance, confidence & love for yourself.
Happy deep dive, my friends 🌈 #thewalkhomepod

I wasn’t even having (intercourse) sex yet, but I was recently diagnosed with ovarian cysts. 
This was said to help with the pain.
And it did.
For 15 years, I took a variety of hormonal birth controls until the end of 2018 when I decided to get my IUD taken out.
It’s been almost 2 years since that day & I’ve still experienced a wide variety of symptoms (ranging from mild, to downright brutal) as my body regulates again.
My mental health was most affected as my hormone levels swung from one extreme to another.
And on January 1, 2019 I sat on the beach in Byron Bay crying in the sand & thinking about how I wanted to die.
I didn’t see how living in that kind of pain was possible, but slowly- as I leaned into the right resources- it was.
During my recovery period post birth control, I found @alisa.vitti and her life’s work @floliving.
Since devouring her book, In the Flo- I’ve also had multiple appts with hormonal specialists on her team who have continued to support me even in the lowest times.
Since implementing subtle changes throughout my monthly cycle, I’ve finally landed in a place where my periods are no longer my worst enemy.
But rather, another source of biofeedback to better understand my inner working’s & my body’s needs.
Needless to say, I was BEYOND thrilled (and super nervous!) to interview her on @Thewalkhomepod for Hormonal Health month.
Regardless of if you’re a person who bleeds, or not, I KNOW our conversation will be eye opening, empowering & incredibly informative.
Alisa is a wealth of knowledge, with a passion so fierce- it’s impossible not to feel lit up in her presence. 
Give it a listen.
See for yourself.

node.text:
Trip out that you’ve been in the same body your WHOLE LIFE?
I do.
All the time.
It almost seems crazy to me that this same body has taken different shapes, sizes & forms.
This body has experienced pain, strength, injury, illness & endurance, alike.
It’s been all over the world.
It’s consumed all kinds of food & all sorts of energy.
It’s interacted with thousands of people & it’s shared intimacy, shame, heartbreak & love with some of them.
Sure, the cells have shed & renewed.
Muscles have formed, atrophied & then re-formed again.
Fat has accumulated, dissolved & returned.
My hair has changed from blonde to brown to streaks of gray.
My skin has loosened & wrinkled, while my tattoos have bled & faded.
But when I think of what’s stayed the same, I think of the way my eyes still sparkle mischievously like they did when I was just a young girl.
I think of the way my face nearly splits in two when I let out a genuine smile- an act that tends to make others grin just as big in return.
I think of the way I grit my teeth when I give a REAL hug to people (but mostly animals) that I love.
This body of mine is ever changing, but always the same.
This body of mine has been equally strong as it’s been weak, equally full as it’s been light.
And as much as I love this lifelong suit that carries me from one moment to the next, I also understand how this physical form might be a PART of me, but not the ACTUAL me at all.
I am the twinkle, the smile & the big hug- not the size or the shape or the lined face. 
To think that I’ll be moving & breathing inside this skin & with these same lungs for another 32 years is enough to blow my mind to pieces.
This body of mine.
What a gift 🌻 #GLOWyogafam

node.text:
I can remember the exact moment I learned.
I was at a sleep over in 6th grade with 3 other girls.
Ya know, just doing the whole 90s sleep over thing of staying up late, eating candy, prank calling & telling “secrets.”
There was a point in which one of the girls asked us which part of our body we hated the most.
She said we had to have AT LEAST one, because everyone does.
Her mom told her so.
I was genuinely confused, because I didn’t realize this was something we were just supposed to KNOW. 
In fact, I’d never even thought about it before.
But, I didn’t want to look stupid so I just listened to the other girls talk about their body parts with disgust. 
My body was shaped similarly to one girl, so when she said she HATED her stomach & pinched her extra skin- I made a mental note:
Must hate stomach for being soft.
When it was my turn, I mimicked her answer with my own flare & from that point on, I made a point to keep hating my stomach. 
I was 12-years-old.
Thinking of girls that age sitting in a circle talking about their beautiful bodies that way breaks my fucking heart.
But it also breaks my heart to continue to hear that little girl voice in my own head trying to make me hate something that’s perfect as it is.
It’s important to note that I have thin privilege 1000% over & to understand that the Body Positivity Movement was created for marginalized folks- not for thin, White able-bodied women (who have taken over the messaging).
However, self love is a practice for ALL bodies, regardless of the shape or size or color.
Even those, like myself, with thin privilege still have a lifetime of unlearning to do when it comes to fat phobia & diet culture.
As someone who is deeply ingrained in the “health & wellness” industry, I’m doing my best to continually check in with my own messaging- both to you all & to myself- but I still mess up.
What I’ve been working on over the last decade is using my physical vessel as a tool for liberation, rather than being a prisoner to it.
And it’s my hope that those of you who come to my classes will feel that within yourself, even if it’s just a moment.
Because all of those micro moments will add up. 
Promise 🦋

node.text:
I was dating a guy who chose to have sex with just about every female he encountered (regardless of our “monogamous” relationship). 
Beyond a heavy dose of self-worth, the greatest gift he gave me was after I led him through my sequence I needed to teach to graduate YTT. 
I hated teaching, because I’d get so nervous that I’d literally black out with fear & forget everything- while still managing to have unplanned words spill out my mouth which somehow formed a cohesive class.
After I practiced on him, he looked at me with tears in his eyes & said, “I know you hate teaching, but you have to keep at it once this training is over. You have something really special that comes through & you need to share that with the world.”
I rolled my eyes & muttered a mixture of thank you & denial.
But it stuck with me.
What if he was right?
So I kept saying yes to opportunities, even when (or ESPECIALLY when) it scared the shit out of me.
Slowly but surely, I began to not just tolerate it- but really love it.
Realizing I was more afraid of myself, my voice & my potential than anything.
Then I decided that I’d have classes on @alomoves (which was still Codyapp at the time) one day.
I visualized it almost daily, although not 100% believing it would happen.
When I got the call from the owner asking me to join the team, I felt equally shocked & not surprised at all.
I was SO anxious before I filmed the first time, mostly because I wanted it to be perfect (which is clearly impossible). 
And hey, there’s nothing like practicing in all spandex attire to add an extra dose of self-consciousness to the mix.
The second time I filmed, I was less nervous- but still held firm to the idea of perfectionism both with aesthetic & performance.
It’s not I don’t care at all this time around, because I DO care deeply about what I’ve created.
What I DON’T care about is the extra squishy layer of flesh at my waistband, or the fact that I’ll likely be modifying A LOT to meet my body where it’s at rather than pushing it to make “perfect” lines & shapes.
I’m not in the same physical shape I was before, but I feel more at peace than ever.
Which adds a helluva lot more value to my teaching if you ask me 🌻

Maybe that means moving through deep belly breaths.
Maybe that means juggling & shaking & wiggling all the tension out.
Maybe it means screaming at the top of your lungs.
As you can see, for me that means spending the majority of my practice in some sort of down dogish shape exploring my spine with my breath.
It means feeling into the places I love & hate, alike.
It means meeting myself where I’m at right NOW, in each passing moment- rather than how I want to be, or how I was yesterday. 
For me, the physical practice of asana has been one of my greatest tools for understanding myself better.
When I’m on my mat, in my body with my breath- I feel limitless, small yet expansive & absolutely liberated.
However.
The longer I teach, the more I realize how untrue this experience is for so many. 
Sometimes the reminder of being in one’s body can feel more like a prison, than freedom.
The thought of breathing & moving & feeling all at once is too overwhelming to be enjoyable at all.
I know everyone has their own process & their own ways of coming back to themselves.
But, as someone who has experienced the gift of movement & believes wholeheartedly in the medicine that lives within each shape- I’m committed to keep doing better in the way I articulate & offer these practices to all of you.
I can do better.
I want to do better.
I will do better.
Because this whatever happens on our mats wasn’t made for, nor intended to only serve, thin White able bodies.
I have one final public offering on Zoom this Thursday, 9 am PST (recording available after class if you can’t make it live). 
The only thing I ask of you is to show up with the dedication to move in a way that makes YOU feel free.
See you then 🌻 #GLOWyogafam

node.text:
It would be beautiful if it were a sunrise or sunset, rather the truth: our Mother is on fire.
My heart is breaking witnessing the place I grew up burn.
Flames eating tens of thousands of acres in the forest, while people get evacuated at all hours of day & night.
It hurts.
To live in hazardous air quality, to know how many animals & humans are suffering, to know our Mother is in this much pain.
As ash fell from the sky like the first snowfall of winter, I thought:
“Is this our new normal now?”
Where half the summer (or more) means breathing smoke into our lungs, instead of the fresh mountain air that raised us.
I don’t know what the point of this is other than to express my deep sadness.
And to remind you to stay safe.
Have an evacuation plan in place & keep your loved ones near (including fur babies). 
And also to offer up a prayer of apology to our planet, as well as promise to do better.
Maybe those woo woo thoughts won’t do a damn thing, but maybe they will.
Regardless, it sure won’t hurt to try.

node.text:
Top tip when you feel like you don’t have time for movement:
Choose just ONE song that matches your current mood.
If you’re wanting a more yoga-esque experience, maybe you roll out your mat.
Otherwise even just just a small amount of space will do.
From there, blast your song (headphones or speaker) & close your eyes if that’s comfortable to you.
Commit to moving your body in any way that you want, any way that feels right, any way that you can- just for the duration of that song.
Even on the busiest days, we all have time for that. 
Plus, I’ve found matching the music to my mood helps me to process emotions more effectively.
Moving heavier energy like sadness, grief, shame THROUGH me- rather than bypassing, or shoving it down.
Move.
Breathe.
And give thanks 🌱 #GLOWyogafam

node.text:
My wife has been gone for 2 weeks & we didn’t speak at all for 10 of those days because she was unplugged on a retreat.
One of my favorite quotes from @Estherperelofficial is:
“Fire needs air.”
I think you can understand how this concept is relevant to what we just experienced.
After over a year of 24/7 togetherness in this C*vid era, I’m so grateful we’re able to start living our own lives again.
We are committed to showing up to our relationship as two whole humans & that means we choose to work on ourselves FIRST & foremost.
This can sound selfish, or misaligned to a lot of people.
But the truth is that when we continually understand, love & explore ourselves- this personal work will inevitably impact ALL of our relationships (not only the romantic ones). 
Living independently & in solitude is natural, easy & enjoyable for me.
Meaning that being in a serious, heavily intertwined relationship like the one we have- can be super difficult for me.
Alix’s nature is quite different to me that way, where she thrives in our togetherness & endless cuddle puddles.
Which is why I’m so freaking proud of her for doing what she just did.
Most importantly, I’m proud of her for choosing to this for HERSELF.
Not for me.
Not to make me happy, or proud, or anything in between.
But for herself.
To get to know herself in a way that she came to deeply crave on her own accord.
Sure, we missed the hell out of each other.
And total disconnection for 10 days felt a little strange. 
But having the unwavering support, trust & love from from both us made all the difference 🌈 #GLOWyogafam

node.text:
I feel fully & truly healthy again for the first time in my adult life.
After a really scary dip in mental & physical health during March & April- something finally shifted when I got the help I needed.
To support my physical health, I sought out multiple doctors (internal medicine, endocrinologist, naturopath) for a million blood test, hormonal tests & treatments.
Around the same time, I found a new therapist to support my mental health more wholly.
After three rounds of EBO2 dialysis treatments in the States, regular high dose Vitamin C IVs, weekly Acupunture & herbal remedies- I went back to the jungle in Peru.
I had the privilege of sitting with Ayahuasca again for three ceremonies.
Afterward, I spent three weeks in isolation in the Sacred Valley.
It was here that I felt the benefits of physical, mental & spiritual healing begin to really settle in.
I was worried when I came back to the States that I would have another bad flare up, end up hospitalized again, get sucked into stress & the MORENESS of our culture.
But after two months, I can proudly say that I’m contributing to implement the lessons I accumulated in the jungle & in the Valley.
I carry peace, trust & joy in me in a way I’ve never felt before. 
That’s not to say that I don’t ever have dips, experience frustration, sadness or disappointment.
Because these two months back have also been incredible challenging emotionally.
But the difference is that I don’t let the stress take the drive seat & own me.
I feel confident in my capability of navigating life & I actually TRUST the curveballs chucked my way.
Today, after my practice, I cried tears of gratitude because I have the privilege to access all these treatments & specialist.
And I cried tears of gratitude for my health.
The silver lining of these chronic illnesses has been the profound shift in my psyche & my heart as I have the gift of approaching life with the same appreciation as a freaking newborn.
My commitment from this point on is to pay it forward by showing up more completely as a teacher, a friend, a family member.
Thank you thank you thank you 🌈 #GLOWyogafam
Image x @miradanomade

node.text:
I used to not let myself eat before filming, even though I had hours of intense physical activity ahead.
Moving around in a spandex suit with multiple cameras on you catching every angle was enough to terrify me into starvation.
I wasn’t focused on how I wanted to FEEL.
Instead, I cared a lot more about how I wanted to LOOK.
Last week I shared some tips about what I do now during big film weeks & one of them was to eat MORE than usual.
This jumped out at me, because only just last year- I still had a lot of fear around food, movement & content creation.
It took a lot of work to undo a lifetime of conditioning around what it means to live in an female’s body.
And it took a lot of work to tell those body fears to fuck right off.
Now I can say with confidence that I do love my body.
But I didn’t go from self hatred to self love right away.
I spent a lot of time in neutrality first- focusing on the actual functionality of certain areas that I didn’t like.
Like: my stomach is soft & has fat because my body can grow a freaking HUMAN inside of me.
Or, my skin protects me.
From there, I (eventually) found gratitude for these functions. 
And that gratitude evolved into love.
This isn’t a linear journey & some days I notice old thought patterns creeping in.
But I decided last year that my mind is a beautiful mansion & renting even just ONE room comes at a high cost.
I won’t be paying rent to the body image room anymore.
It’s too expensive.
Because it gets in the way of living a truly happy & fulfilled life. 
Now, I’m free 🌈 #GLOWyogafam

I left Alo Moves to protect my mental health.
3 years ago when they asked me to teach, I was THRILLED & flattered that I’d be on a platform with world class teachers I’d admired for years.
Then, my mental health- specifically around body image- unraveled.
The thought of having multiple cameras capturing every inch of me, rather than my usual meticulously angled content on IG, was terrifying.
Looking back, it sounds so silly & sad.
What’s so scary about seeing ME, all of me, AS I AM?
Well, being a perfectionist meant that I wanted to DO my classes perfectly & also wanted to LOOK perfect, too. 
Whatever that means.
I was intimidated by the other teachers’ skill & experience, as well as their seemingly “perfect” physical appearance. 
By the time my first filming came around, I was incredibly unhealthy (mentally & physically).
I was also much thinner than usual due to the self-inflicted pressure & controlled eating.
You’d think I’d be satisfied with the outcome of being super skinny.
But the reality was that it only created MORE pressure to continue to look that way for the next filming & the next & the next & so on. 
I want to be clear in saying no one at Alo Moves ever MADE me feel this way.
This is my own shit. 
In fact, I genuinely loved working alongside their team for the last few years.
I realized that working on a full set with hair & make up & everything immaculately curated was only feeding my insecurities & amplifying my perfectionist tendencies. 
The environment wasn’t healthy for me.
And it was pulling me away from what I really came to do.
Teach.
Signing with Alo Moves was easily one of the most valuable moments in my career so far, because it amplified my teaching across the globe.
And I’ve connected with so many of you because of it.
I’m grateful for that growth & I’m grateful for the hard lessons, because it’s brought me where I am today.
Walking away from a contract that’s given me so much & choosing my mental health instead wasn’t an easy decision to make.
But now that I’m on the other side, I couldn’t be more proud.
I finally feel both free & back at home in myself all at once.
Mental health is health.
Mental health matters.
Don’t forget that.
